{"author":{"id":"b78c39e7b13f90a5827abfba043255fe7a4ede1499df23f110fffe5abfa44adc"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1771617900,"nonce":"2usXV6sa+/eTmhBnBGUL4MGHpgA=","metadata":{"github-id":"I_kwDOQ241x87so-6x","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/249","origin":"github"},"title":"Workspace rework: establish direction and improve incrementally","message":"## Problem\n\nThis workspace has grown organically through iterative agent-assisted development. The result is a capable but sprawling system that's hard to understand holistically:\n\n- **41 scripts** in `.agent/scripts/`, some overlapping, some dead, some undocumented\n- **20 Makefile targets**, most thin wrappers, no single setup entrypoint\n- **5+ documentation files** (README, CLAUDE.md, ARCHITECTURE.md, WORKTREE_GUIDE.md, AI_RULES.md, etc.) with overlapping and sometimes contradictory guidance\n- **Features that exist but aren't reliably followed** — e.g., draft PR creation during work was implemented but may not be consistently enforced; the worktree-first workflow is documented but agents still edit the main tree\n\nThe result: both humans and agents struggle to answer \"what does this workspace do, and how do I use it correctly?\" Ideas get implemented, then lost in the noise.\n\n## Goal\n\nDistill this workspace down to its essential features and workflows, with the **README as the authoritative guide** for both using and improving the workspace. The README should be:\n\n- **Complete**: Everything you need to know to use the workspace effectively\n- **Concise**: Not overwhelming — a product manual, not an encyclopedia\n- **Canonical**: The single source of truth that other docs (CLAUDE.md, AI_RULES.md) reference rather than duplicate\n\n## Proposed Approach\n\n### Phase 1: Audit and Classify\n\nInventory everything the workspace provides and classify each item:\n\n| Category | Keep | Deprecate | Consolidate |\n|----------|------|-----------|-------------|\n| Scripts | Which are actually used? | Dead code (e.g., `generate_knowledge.sh` no-op) | Overlapping tools (3 identity scripts, 2 issue-start workflows) |\n| Makefile targets | Core operations | Rarely-used targets | `setup-*` into single `setup` |\n| Documentation | Essential guides | Outdated docs | Scattered info into README |\n| Workflows | Proven patterns | Aspirational but unused | Fragmented steps into clear flows |\n\n### Phase 2: Simplify the Interface\n\n**Makefile**: Reduce to a clean, memorable set of targets with a single setup entrypoint:\n```\nmake setup          # Bootstrap + repos + venv + hooks + skills — everything\nmake build          # Build all layers\nmake test           # Run all tests\nmake status         # Full workspace status\nmake lint           # Run linters\nmake clean          # Clean build artifacts\nmake help           # Show available targets\n```\n\nKeep scripts behind the scenes — simplify what's presented to the user.\n\n**Scripts**: Move internal helpers to a subdirectory (e.g., `scripts/lib/`). Deprecate and remove dead code. Consolidate overlapping tools.\n\n### Phase 3: Rewrite the README\n\nStructure the README as the single guide:\n\n1. **What this is** — one paragraph\n2. **Quick start** — clone, setup, build (3 commands)\n3. **Key workflows** — develop (worktree flow), build \u0026 test, status \u0026 monitoring\n4. **For AI agents** — pointer to framework-specific instruction files\n5. **Architecture** — brief layered workspace explanation (inline, not a separate doc)\n6. **Customization** — using with other projects, adding layers\n7. **Development tools** — Makefile reference, scripts overview\n8. **Contributing** — how to improve this workspace\n\n### Phase 4: Align Agent Instructions\n\nUpdate CLAUDE.md, AI_RULES.md, and other agent docs to **reference the README** for workflows rather than duplicating them. Agent docs should only contain agent-specific rules (identity, git behavior, tool usage) — not re-explain the workspace.\n\n## Non-Goals\n\n- Not redesigning the architecture (layers, worktrees, etc.)\n- Not rewriting scripts from scratch — just pruning and reorganizing\n- Not adding new features — this is about clarity and consolidation\n\n## Discussion Points\n\n- Which Makefile targets do you actually use regularly?\n- Are there scripts or workflows that were experiments and never stuck?\n- Should the `agent` script become the primary agent interface (subcommands like `agent build`, `agent test`), or stay focused on worktree management?\n- How much of ARCHITECTURE.md and WORKTREE_GUIDE.md should fold into the README vs. remain separate?\n\n---\n**Authored-By**: `Claude Code Agent`\n**Model**: `Claude Opus 4.6`","files":null}]}